                    
Week 1
                             Basic Unix commands
                             
Unix users commands:These commands allow to get basic information about Unix users in ours environment.

//shows the user
rgukt-basar@123:~$ whoami
rgukt-basar

//System id
rgukt-basar@123:~$ id
uid=1000(rgukt-basar) gid=1000(rgukt-basar) groups=1000(rgukt-basar),4(adm),24(cdrom),27(sudo),30(dip),46(plugdev),122(lpadmin),134(lxd),135(sambashare)
rgukt-basar@12

//groups – show which groups user belongs to
rgukt-basar@123:~$ groups
rgukt-basar adm cdrom sudo dip plugdev lpadmin lxd sambashare

//to know the directory which u r in
rgukt-basar@123:~$ pwd
/home/rgukt-basar

//To find out who logged into our system
rgukt-basar@123:~$ who
rgukt-basar tty2         2024-03-19 14:53 (tty2)

//last – show history of logins into the system
rgukt-basar@123:~$last
rgukt-ba tty2         tty2             Sat Apr  6 14:58   still logged in
reboot   system boot  6.5.0-25-generic Sat Apr  6 14:58   still running
rgukt-ba tty2         tty2             Wed Apr  3 14:30 - down   (00:10)
reboot   system boot  6.5.0-25-generic Wed Apr  3 14:30 - 14:41  (00:10)
rgukt-ba tty2         tty2             Sat Mar 30 20:47 - down   (00:01)
reboot   system boot  6.5.0-25-generic Sat Mar 30 20:46 - 20:48  (00:01)

              Unix file operations
              
Navigating filesystem and managing files and access permissions:
cp – copy files (work in progress)
rm – remove files and directories (work in progress)
mv – rename or move files and directories to another location
echo – “hello world”
chown – change file/directory ownership
            
            Unix directory management commands
Navigating filesystems and managing directories:


//to create a directories(folder)
rgukt-basar@123:~$ mkdir sun

//cd – change directory
rgukt-basar@123:~$ cd ~/Downloads
rgukt-basar@123:~/Downloads$ cd ~/

//ls -shows what are there in laptop

//to remove directory
rgukt-basar@123:~$ rmdir sun

             Control Commands:
             
      ctrl+c:this command terminates the currently running oreground process.
 ctrl+D:this command terminates the currently running login or terminal session
 ctrl+Z:This command suspends the cunnently ruuning foreground process to the background.
        
//to create file
rgukt-basar@123:~$ cat> sunflower
hello sunflower
ubuntu
